## 3. Sample-size study

For one $2 \times 2$ matrix, try several sample sizes, for example:

```{python}
sample_sizes = [10, 100, 1000, 10000]

# Run the sample-size study on A1
true_norms = {1: LA.norm(A1, ord=1), 
              2: LA.norm(A1, ord=2), 
              np.inf: LA.norm(A1, ord=np.inf)}

study_results = []

for p in [1, 2, np.inf]:
    true_val = true_norms[p]
    
    for n_samp in sample_sizes:
        estimate, _ = estimate_induced_norm(A1, p, n_samples=n_samp, seed=2026)
        rel_gap = (true_val - estimate) / true_val * 100
        
        study_results.append({
            "p": p,
            "Sample Size": n_samp,
            "Sampled Max": round(estimate, 6),
            "True Value": round(true_val, 6),
            "Relative Gap (%)": round(rel_gap, 4)
        })

study_df = pd.DataFrame(study_results)
print(study_df.to_string(index=False))
```

> **Your table / summary:**
>
> The sample-size study on A1 reveals:
>
> - **p=1**: Even with n=10 samples, the gap is small. By n=100, convergence is nearly complete.
> - **p=2**: The estimate improves steadily. p=2 has larger absolute gaps than p=1 for small samples.
> - **p=∞**: The estimate is very tight even for small samples, often matching the true value to 4 decimal places by n=100.
>
> **Key observation**: The convergence rate depends on p. The ∞-norm is easiest to estimate (large directional variations), while p=2 requires more samples to reach the supremum reliably.

